      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Prevent Asthma</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Paul G Rogers says less than 1 percent of federal budget is spent on asthma prevention research (May 22 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Study Finds Most States Lack System for Monitoring Asthma'' (news article, May 22):</p>
        <p>Your article points out the large number of resources needed to gather information for the prevention of asthma. But financing lags far behind. Less than 1 percent of the federal budget is spent on prevention research.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Study Finds Most States Lack System for Monitoring Asthma'' (news article, May 22):</p>
        <p>Your article points out the large number of resources needed to gather information for the prevention of asthma. But financing lags far behind. Less than 1 percent of the federal budget is spent on prevention research.</p>
        <p>As Congress continues the commitment to double financing for medical and health research by 2003, it is essential that it approve commensurate increases for prevention, population-based, behavioral and health services research.</p>
        <p>Only then will we be able to breathe easier.</p>
        <p>PAUL G. ROGERS  Alexandria, Va., May 24, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is chairman of Research America.</p>
      </block>
